The Education ministry has outlined tight regulations to ensure learning is not disrupted as the country heads to the polls.In a circular to county directors, regional coordinators and school heads, the ministry has outlined guidelines that it seeks to follow to ensure no disruption occurs.The guidelines require normal teaching and learning to continue in all institutions with no disruption from political parties or politicians during the campaigns.The political parties have been advised to avoid taking politics within learning institutions.&ldquo;All interactions between political parties and educational institutions should be structured, formal and documented,&rdquo; the circular reads. Heads of boarding institutions have also been advised to reside within school compounds.